who married someone here.

00:09:47.800 --> 00:09:50.480
I don't know how she ended up
in Louisiana to begin with.

00:09:50.480 --> 00:09:52.210
We need to find that out.

00:09:52.210 --> 00:09:54.560
But I learned a lot
from my grandfather,

00:09:54.560 --> 00:09:58.580 position:56%
who went from having nothing when he
arrived to becoming very successful

00:09:58.580 --> 00:10:02.470
in business and banking and
giving me, two generations later,

00:10:02.470 --> 00:10:05.140
this tremendous opportunity
to stand before you.

00:10:05.140 --> 00:10:08.690
First as a very successful
cardiac surgeon and now

00:10:08.690 --> 00:10:11.350
with a career in public office.

00:10:11.350 --> 00:10:12.920
And I owe so much to him.

00:10:12.920 --> 00:10:16.230
But one of the most important
things he told me and imbued

00:10:16.230 --> 00:10:20.010
in me was not only a love of
reading and reading history.

00:10:20.010 --> 00:10:22.620
But he taught me about my heritage.

00:10:22.620 --> 00:10:23.950
I might not have known.

00:10:23.950 --> 00:10:28.920
And the first time I ever heard
about the Phoenicians was sitting

00:10:28.920 --> 00:10:31.000
on the lap of my grandfather
when I was a young child.

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:34.120
And his intense sense
of pride was amazing.

00:10:34.120 --> 00:10:38.390
And I remember he told me
after the first World War,

00:10:38.390 --> 00:10:41.020
he went back to Lebanon
to find his mother.

00:10:41.020 --> 00:10:43.290
His father had passed
away in the interim time.

00:10:43.290 --> 00:10:45.610
He found his brother who was
on the verge of starvation.

00:10:45.610 --> 00:10:48.790
And this is just one of many, many
stories I'm sure have been repeated

00:10:48.790 --> 00:10:51.000
across America with
a Lebanese diaspora.

00:10:51.000 --> 00:10:54.880 position:56%
But when you reflect on the Lebanese
diaspora, it's quite amazing.

00:10:54.880 --> 00:10:57.690
Because there are people
all across this country

00:10:57.690 --> 00:11:02.680
who have reached the pinnacle of
their professions or chosen line

00:11:02.680 --> 00:11:06.080 position:56%
of work, whether it's the arts,
sciences, or professions in medicine

00:11:06.080 --> 00:11:07.660
and law, education and so forth.

00:11:07.660 --> 00:11:08.960
It's quite amazing.

00:11:08.960 --> 00:11:10.930
And I wasn't really aware
of this until I actually got

00:11:10.930 --> 00:11:15.570 position:56%
into public office and began to meet
so many across this great country.

00:11:15.570 --> 00:11:17.440
But my grandfather
taught me about history.

00:11:17.440 --> 00:11:19.360
And that love of history
never went away.

00:11:19.360 --> 00:11:21.500
And I embarked on reading

00:11:21.500 --> 00:11:25.510
and studying ancient
Mediterranean history.

00:11:25.510 --> 00:11:29.930 position:56%
And fast forward, I took a course
on ancient civilizations in college.

00:11:29.930 --> 00:11:33.730
And there was a history
professor there, long deceased,

00:11:33.730 --> 00:11:37.350
who had a profound impact on me
despite all my education science.

00:11:37.350 --> 00:11:41.060
This one class furthered
my love of history,

00:11:41.060 --> 00:11:44.550
took it to a different level
for me and taught me one thing

00:11:44.550 --> 00:11:48.290
that I have never forgotten,
that history is a living thing.

00:11:48.290 --> 00:11:52.520
It's not old dates and
artifacts that have gone away

00:11:52.520 --> 00:11:54.930
and they're collecting dust.

00:11:54.930 --> 00:11:56.230
History is living.

00:11:56.230 --> 00:11:57.800
It affects us today.

00:11:57.800 --> 00:12:00.190
And I think that is
incredibly relevant.

00:12:00.190 --> 00:12:02.680
That's why this symposium
is so important.

00:12:02.680 --> 00:12:05.330
Just take for a moment, I'll give
you just a few more reflections

00:12:05.330 --> 00:12:07.630
on that before I close.

00:12:07.630 --> 00:12:10.790
First of all, we all know what's
happening across the Middle East

00:12:10.790 --> 00:12:13.590
with the tremendous chaos
and the difficulties,

00:12:13.590 --> 00:12:16.240
much of it playing out in Lebanon.

00:12:16.240 --> 00:12:20.540
Well, antiquity is being
destroyed across the world

00:12:20.540 --> 00:12:22.960
as a result of some of this.

00:12:22.960 --> 00:12:26.240 position:56%
This is something that's not getting
the kind of attention it needs.

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:31.790
And hopefully this symposium with
publicity surrounding it will put

00:12:31.790 --> 00:12:33.490
that into the public domain.

00:12:33.490 --> 00:12:36.420
We are having conversations
about that in Congress.

00:12:36.420 --> 00:12:38.850
But it's so important to
preserve these antiquities

00:12:38.850 --> 00:12:42.630
because they have impact
on us today.

00:12:42.630 --> 00:12:48.240
Let me just reflect for just a
moment on the city-state of Tyre

00:12:48.240 --> 00:12:54.000
and what is now Lebanon but was
a Phoenician empire in days past.

00:12:54.000 --> 00:12:57.780
Tyre is regarded as the greatest
maritime trading civilization

00:12:57.780 --> 00:12:59.080
in the world.

00:12:59.080 --> 00:13:02.900
And you all know the stories about
how the alphabet and so forth.

00:13:02.900 --> 00:13:06.070
Trade is critically important
and it's relevant today.

00:13:06.070 --> 00:13:08.990
This is a heated debate we're
having in Congress today

00:13:08.990 --> 00:13:13.190
on whether America will embark
on a very aggressive trade policy

00:13:13.190 --> 00:13:16.130
and provide that kind of
leadership to bring us together

00:13:16.130 --> 00:13:18.450
through commercial relationships.

00:13:18.450 --> 00:13:20.530
I think an avenue for peace.

00:13:20.530 --> 00:13:23.910
Or will we back away from
trade, become more isolationist

00:13:23.910 --> 00:13:29.580
in our own views and basically give
up American leadership globally?

00:13:29.580 --> 00:13:34.620
So what happened in ancient
civilization when the understanding

00:13:34.620 --> 00:13:38.200
of the importance of trade was
not quite so well understood,

00:13:38.200 --> 00:13:43.390
the creativity of the Phoenician
civilization was quite amazing.

00:13:43.390 --> 00:13:45.720
And it was centered upon Tyre.

00:13:45.720 --> 00:13:49.350
So we have a lot to learn
by studying the history,

00:13:49.350 --> 00:13:52.620
learning from the mistakes
that were made,

00:13:52.620 --> 00:13:55.220
but also the great
advances that were made.

00:13:55.220 --> 00:13:58.410
So I want to thank you all
