00:40:28.040 --> 00:40:33.910 position:56%
The subject of my presentation is
the first Phoenician temple in Tyre,

00:40:33.910 --> 00:40:41.410
which we have recently
excavated in Tyre.

00:40:41.410 --> 00:40:46.190
By launching a new excavation
project in Tyre, the main objective

00:40:46.190 --> 00:40:50.230
of the American University of
Beirut museum team was first

00:40:50.230 --> 00:40:55.420
to reach the Phoenician levels of
the famous Phoenician city of Tyre.

00:40:55.420 --> 00:41:00.620
The second target was to discover
the assumed temple whose possible

00:41:00.620 --> 00:41:03.480
location was mentioned
to us by Mr. Badouwi,

00:41:03.480 --> 00:41:07.030 position:56%
the director of antiquities in Tyre.

00:41:07.030 --> 00:41:10.800
The early temples of
Tyre have been mentioned

00:41:10.800 --> 00:41:13.320
in several historical sources.

00:41:13.320 --> 00:41:18.240
To mention but a couple,
first the legend of Karat

00:41:18.240 --> 00:41:23.030
from the 14th century when King
Karat stopped building his district

00:41:23.030 --> 00:41:25.830
at the shrine of [inaudible]
of Tyre.

00:41:25.830 --> 00:41:29.920
This temple was probably
located on the mainland.

00:41:29.920 --> 00:41:34.800
Second, Hiram's builders in the
5th century BC gave a detailed

00:41:34.800 --> 00:41:39.030
description of the temple
of Heracles, the main temple

00:41:39.030 --> 00:41:41.500
of Tyre which had two columns.

00:41:41.500 --> 00:41:45.880
One of gold and one of emerald.

00:41:45.880 --> 00:41:52.190
But the most important
iconographic source where the city

00:41:52.190 --> 00:41:56.610
of Tyre is presented in a
sculpture believed from the palace

00:41:56.610 --> 00:42:02.570
of Sennacherib in Nineveh,
dated to 690 BC.

00:42:02.570 --> 00:42:08.160
A temple, probably that of
Melkar is depicted above the port

00:42:08.160 --> 00:42:14.640
with two free-standing columns as
you see it indicated by the arrow.

00:42:17.090 --> 00:42:22.420
The site which we selected
to excavate is located

00:42:22.420 --> 00:42:25.100
on the island of Phoenician Tyre.

00:42:25.100 --> 00:42:29.820
It's a known fact that ancient
Tyre was originally a rocky island,

00:42:29.820 --> 00:42:33.210
hence it's Phoenician name, Sour.

00:42:33.210 --> 00:42:38.110
Alexander the Great joined it
later to the mainland by a causeway

00:42:38.110 --> 00:42:41.740
over which sand deposits
accumulated through the years,

00:42:41.740 --> 00:42:44.730
forming an artificial isthmus.

00:42:44.730 --> 00:42:53.440 position:56%
This island appears now as a
peninsula stretching out to the sea.

00:42:53.440 --> 00:43:03.060
What did our site of sector seven
look like before the investigation?

00:43:03.060 --> 00:43:09.270
After the departure of Emir
Shihab from Tyre at the break

00:43:09.270 --> 00:43:15.200
of the Lebanese War in 1975, the
sector seven which is located

00:43:15.200 --> 00:43:16.710
within the Phoenician island

00:43:16.710 --> 00:43:22.650
of Tyre had been abandoned
for nearly 40 years.

00:43:22.650 --> 00:43:27.380
The consequence of this
abandonment resulted in the growing

00:43:27.380 --> 00:43:33.280
of a four-meter high reed forest
which covered the entire area

00:43:33.280 --> 00:43:38.170
to be investigated by
the AUB museum team.

00:43:38.170 --> 00:43:43.570
To our great surprise, some
ancient walls began to appear.

00:43:43.570 --> 00:43:49.340
But the greater surprise was that
the site had already been excavated

00:43:49.340 --> 00:43:54.550
by Emir Shihab some 40 years ago
without anyone knowing about it.

00:43:54.550 --> 00:43:58.110
Not a single report or
archive were available

00:43:58.110 --> 00:44:01.220
to indicate this earlier discovery.

00:44:01.220 --> 00:44:08.010
Yet in the process of my research
I discovered the following lines

00:44:08.010 --> 00:44:11.650
written by Shihab in 1979
of the first Phoenician

00:44:11.650 --> 00:44:13.870
and Punic Congress in Rome.

00:44:13.870 --> 00:44:17.720
He mentioned among other results
of his excavations in Tyre

00:44:17.720 --> 00:44:22.710
in 1973 a large Phoenician monument

00:44:22.710 --> 00:44:27.980
with a 10-meter long wall
that we will show later.

00:44:27.980 --> 00:44:33.380
It's obvious that Emir Shihab
did not recognize then the nature

00:44:33.380 --> 00:44:38.520
of this vast monument
as he mentioned it.

00:44:38.520 --> 00:44:42.920
Our luck was that this
monument clearly refers

00:44:42.920 --> 00:44:47.680
to the temple we were
about to excavate.

00:44:47.680 --> 00:44:53.610
Our task was therefore
to rediscover the site

00:44:53.610 --> 00:44:57.330
and to complete Shihab's
excavation in view

00:44:57.330 --> 00:45:02.450
of analyzing this important
monument, documenting it,

00:45:02.450 --> 00:45:05.930
interpreting its function
and attempting

00:45:05.930 --> 00:45:09.230
to determine its historical
chronology.

00:45:09.230 --> 00:45:18.040
The temple in sector seven was
located under the residential area

00:45:18.040 --> 00:45:23.630
of the classical period, which
extended further to the northwest.

00:45:23.630 --> 00:45:27.220
What did we actually discover?

00:45:27.220 --> 00:45:32.600
From the first two weeks and
after sketching a working plan

00:45:32.600 --> 00:45:37.330
of the archaeological remains, we
could already assume that we were

00:45:37.330 --> 00:45:42.880
in front of a temple due to the
presence of a massive construction

00:45:42.880 --> 00:45:44.570
which could clearly and

00:45:44.570 --> 00:45:49.020
yet tentatively be
identified as a podium.

00:45:49.020 --> 00:45:56.360 position:56%
The temple has a rectangular shape,
21 meters long and 6.50 meters wide.

00:45:56.360 --> 00:46:02.050
Its axis is oriented
northwest/southeast.

00:46:02.050 --> 00:46:05.480
Several structures were
found within the temple.

00:46:05.480 --> 00:46:10.760
First of all, the podium which
is two meter high structure.

00:46:10.760 --> 00:46:14.710
It consists of a foundation
course, surrounded by three courses

00:46:14.710 --> 00:46:18.740
of very large blocks
in hard sandstone.

00:46:18.740 --> 00:46:23.830
The setting follows the structure
and [inaudible] which is well-known

00:46:23.830 --> 00:46:26.970
in the Phoenician architecture.

00:46:26.970 --> 00:46:31.800
The blocks of this podium can
be compared in size to those

00:46:31.800 --> 00:46:37.540 position:56%
of the podium of the Eshmun temple
that you can see on the lower photo.

00:46:42.160 --> 00:46:47.230
Which are close in length to ours
but are double in width and height

00:46:47.230 --> 00:46:50.660
with a weight of two
tons and a half.

00:46:50.660 --> 00:46:53.740
Those of Eshmun.

00:46:53.740 --> 00:46:57.620
The Eshmun temple is a
gigantic one by its size.

00:46:57.620 --> 00:47:00.970
It is inspired by the
Babylonian Ziggurat.

00:47:00.970 --> 00:47:07.130
It is 22 meters high, but its
podium alone has been preserved.

00:47:07.130 --> 00:47:10.960
None of the temple
has been preserved.

00:47:10.960 --> 00:47:16.830
Our Tyre temple blocks were
constructed in the nearby quarries

00:47:16.830 --> 00:47:20.980
which are partly under
the seawater today.

00:47:20.980 --> 00:47:28.170
Two sings that are
shown on the podium.

00:47:28.170 --> 00:47:33.550
One letter is M like
the McDonald M, and Z,

00:47:33.550 --> 00:47:36.030
were incised on the upper block.

00:47:36.030 --> 00:47:39.780
These are probably the
signatures of the masons

00:47:39.780 --> 00:47:42.900
which were used for
accounting purpose.

00:47:42.900 --> 00:47:45.230
Similar signs have been identified

00:47:45.230 --> 00:47:50.670
on a contemporary documented
building in Byblos.

00:47:50.670 --> 00:47:54.910
On top of the podium,
an altar was placed.

00:47:54.910 --> 00:48:00.100
It is a very large monolithic
single-stone slab made

00:48:00.100 --> 00:48:02.820
out of marine limestone.

00:48:02.820 --> 00:48:10.390
This altar presents a wavy surface
which may suggest hypothetically

00:48:10.390 --> 00:48:14.810
that it was used intentionally
in order to make the flowing

00:48:14.810 --> 00:48:17.900
of the sacrificial blood possible.

00:48:17.900 --> 00:48:25.340
A massive structure
located on the eastern end

00:48:25.340 --> 00:48:34.050
of the temple is built opposite and
symmetrical to the podium you see

00:48:34.050 --> 00:48:37.190
on the massive structure.

00:48:37.190 --> 00:48:40.500
And the podium on the upper part.

00:48:40.500 --> 00:48:43.530
One could imagine that this
structure could have been the

00:48:43.530 --> 00:48:49.220
foundation of a massive
structure, maybe a tower.

00:48:49.220 --> 00:48:54.940
And that this tower may have
had a niche in which the deity

00:48:54.940 --> 00:48:58.980
of the temple would have been
placed facing the podium.

00:48:58.980 --> 00:49:03.820
This was the case in
many oriental temples.

00:49:03.820 --> 00:49:09.430
The plan of the temple is
indicated by a large rectangle.

00:49:09.430 --> 00:49:12.760
The average preservation
of the walls is one course,

00:49:12.760 --> 00:49:14.950
but sometimes six courses.

00:49:14.950 --> 00:49:19.910
They are made out of fine sandstone
blocks nearly half size compared

00:49:19.910 --> 00:49:21.410
to the blocks of the podium.

00:49:21.410 --> 00:49:25.760
And this is how we could
immediately identify the podium.

00:49:25.760 --> 00:49:32.710
Because it's totally much
bigger blocks than the walls.

00:49:32.710 --> 00:49:39.550
The walls are generally set
in regular structure pattern

00:49:39.550 --> 00:49:43.110
as you see in the lower photo.

00:49:43.110 --> 00:49:47.730
The two long walls of the temple
are built against the western wall

00:49:47.730 --> 00:49:51.610
which is the western
limit of the temple.

00:49:51.610 --> 00:49:57.910
This view shows the inner
façade of the western wall.

00:49:57.910 --> 00:50:01.660
Its external façade is
beautifully decorated

00:50:01.660 --> 00:50:05.420
with a long continuous
horizontal phrase

00:50:05.420 --> 00:50:09.160
of what we call Egyptian courses.

00:50:09.160 --> 00:50:12.350
It consists of five
preserved courses

00:50:12.350 --> 00:50:15.880
with finely dressed sandstone
blocks tightly set together

00:50:15.880 --> 00:50:22.140
with very thin joints and
without any bonding material.

00:50:22.140 --> 00:50:26.650
The same architectural decorative
Egyptian gorges are known

00:50:26.650 --> 00:50:31.830
from the Phoenician temple in
Amrit on the coast of Syria

00:50:31.830 --> 00:50:38.480
where it decorates the
upper part of its towers.

00:50:38.480 --> 00:50:46.280
Similarly, at the Eshmun temple
near Sidon, the same type of blocks

00:50:46.280 --> 00:50:49.320
with the Egyptian gorges
have been noted

00:50:49.320 --> 00:50:53.890
by our team during a site
visit to the Eshmun temple.

00:50:56.390 --> 00:51:01.070
Some hydraulic installations,
wells and basins which are common

00:51:01.070 --> 00:51:05.750
in the Phoenician temples have
been found around our temple.

00:51:05.750 --> 00:51:11.190
They testified to the important
role that water rituals played

00:51:11.190 --> 00:51:15.960
in Phoenician therapeutic
cults as it is emphasized

00:51:15.960 --> 00:51:19.780
in both Eshmun and Amrit temples.

00:51:22.720 --> 00:51:29.740
This basin has four steps
that leads to its bottom.

00:51:30.970 --> 00:51:41.090
It could have been used for
purposes in relation to the temple.

00:51:41.090 --> 00:51:42.990
The main problem we faced was

00:51:42.990 --> 00:51:47.600
to find the temple entrance,
which we finally found.

00:51:47.600 --> 00:51:54.590
About the center of the
western wall we found this setup

00:51:54.590 --> 00:51:58.010
or these structures.

00:51:58.010 --> 00:52:03.630
The lowest platform which will
present the earliest circulation

00:52:03.630 --> 00:52:09.000
level of the temple built with
huge blocks about one meter long.

00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:15.170
It leads into a two-meter wide
opening with a door socket.

00:52:15.170 --> 00:52:20.940 position:56%
The width of which exists throughout
various areas of the entrance.

00:52:20.940 --> 00:52:25.860
The middle platform is built
directly on top of the earlier one,

00:52:25.860 --> 00:52:29.540
and it is also dotted
with a door socket.

00:52:29.540 --> 00:52:36.610
A third paved platform entrance
was added to the two previous ones.

00:52:36.610 --> 00:52:42.800
It is set between two
walls which were built

00:52:42.800 --> 00:52:46.510
between the two lateral walls
of the temple and which served

00:52:46.510 --> 00:52:50.930
as arch support for
this paved floor.

00:52:50.930 --> 00:52:56.010
We suppose as a hypothesis that
this pavement could have extended

00:52:56.010 --> 00:52:57.360
with a slight ramp.

00:52:57.360 --> 00:53:01.200 position:56%
You can see it on the lower picture.

00:53:01.200 --> 00:53:04.250
Towards the east to
reach the embossed level

00:53:04.250 --> 00:53:07.380
of the first course of the podium.

00:53:07.380 --> 00:53:11.370
With this hypothesis it is
possible to imagine the entrance

00:53:11.370 --> 00:53:13.730
of the temple from the west side,

00:53:13.730 --> 00:53:17.280
not the east as it
is usually the case

00:53:17.280 --> 00:53:21.760
in the Phoenician or
oriental temples.

00:53:21.760 --> 00:53:25.930
This would lead directly
to the altar level in view

00:53:25.930 --> 00:53:29.120
of the execution of the sacrifice.

00:53:29.120 --> 00:53:34.280
A kiln is built against the
eastern façade of the podium.

00:53:34.280 --> 00:53:36.940
Two oblique altar stands placed

00:53:36.940 --> 00:53:41.710
in an inverted V shape
mark its doorway opening.

00:53:41.710 --> 00:53:45.580
Black traces can be
seen on its upper part.

00:53:45.580 --> 00:53:49.890
And gray ashes are
found near the doorway.

00:53:49.890 --> 00:53:55.070
An important burn deposit
mixed with ashes

00:53:55.070 --> 00:53:59.050
and small charcoal bits was
found opposite the kiln.

00:53:59.050 --> 00:54:02.690
A small section of this deposit
was collected and sifted,

00:54:02.690 --> 00:54:06.780
producing 17 buckets
of small animal bones.

00:54:06.780 --> 00:54:11.470
It seems pretty obvious that
the animals of rather small

00:54:11.470 --> 00:54:15.870
or medium size, which were
sacrificed on top of the altar,

00:54:15.870 --> 00:54:20.030
were probably thrown directly
in the cremation kiln.

00:54:20.030 --> 00:54:27.740
The presence of a few items found
around the temple may be considered

00:54:27.740 --> 00:54:31.770 position:56%
as offerings to the temple divinity.

00:54:31.770 --> 00:54:34.710
Among these, one [inaudible] found

00:54:34.710 --> 00:54:41.000
by our colleague Dr. Eddie
Curel outside the temple.

00:54:52.060 --> 00:54:55.070
The presence of few
items may be considered

00:54:55.070 --> 00:54:59.630 position:56%
as offerings to the temple divinity.

00:54:59.630 --> 00:55:05.050 position:56%
One [inaudible], as I said, found by
Dr. Curel, two large stone anchors,

00:55:05.050 --> 00:55:10.400
a few lamp fragments, not to
forget the burnt animal bones found

00:55:10.400 --> 00:55:13.540
in the deposit in the
vicinity of the kiln.

00:55:13.540 --> 00:55:20.870
All these are extra evidence that
our monument is indeed a temple.

00:55:20.870 --> 00:55:23.210
Chronological conclusions.

00:55:23.210 --> 00:55:27.360
As we have indicated
earlier, in the total absence

00:55:27.360 --> 00:55:31.820
of stratigraphic records and the
lack of pottery materials found

00:55:31.820 --> 00:55:34.510
in C2, it's rather
difficult at this stage

00:55:34.510 --> 00:55:39.160
to draw any final chronological
conclusions.

00:55:39.160 --> 00:55:41.860
Because most of the
pottery is mixed,

00:55:41.860 --> 00:55:49.320
we can only draw some
post-antiquan periods, the end.

00:55:49.320 --> 00:55:53.180
From the Persian to
the Hellenistic period.

00:55:53.180 --> 00:55:56.250
On this basis, we may
tentatively conclude

00:55:56.250 --> 00:56:00.900
that the temple itself
belongs to the Persian period.

00:56:00.900 --> 00:56:06.270
This dating is enhanced by the
common architectural features

00:56:06.270 --> 00:56:11.860
and masonry techniques which are
known from the neighboring temples

00:56:11.860 --> 00:56:18.130
of the region, especially from the
Eshmun temple in Sidon and that

00:56:18.130 --> 00:56:22.590 position:56%
of Armit in Syria as stated earlier.

00:56:22.590 --> 00:56:30.840
The underwater sounding [inaudible]
a group of Phoenician pottery.

00:56:30.840 --> 00:56:36.500
This explains the large number of
iron tools that have been collected

00:56:36.500 --> 00:56:40.180
in various points, but not in C2.

00:56:40.180 --> 00:56:46.200 position:56%
This preliminary assessment of the
pottery may hint to a continuous use

00:56:46.200 --> 00:56:52.790
of this temple retaining its sacral
character from the Achaemenid

00:56:52.790 --> 00:56:57.730
to the Hellenistic period and
possibly including the early phases

00:56:57.730 --> 00:57:01.120
of the Roman occupation as well.

00:57:01.120 --> 00:57:06.910 position:56%
As it stands and with all the very
good results we have just presented,

00:57:06.910 --> 00:57:13.070
we may conclude that our newly
rediscovered temple is the first

00:57:13.070 --> 00:57:16.250
Phoenician temple in Tyre

00:57:16.250 --> 00:57:19.920
and the first complete
Phoenician temple in Lebanon.

