01:56:00.170 --> 01:56:04.770
But I'm here to speak about the
coinage or Tyre in antiquity.

01:56:04.770 --> 01:56:09.480
Tyre was one of the most
prominent cities during antiquity.

01:56:09.480 --> 01:56:12.140
Its coinage reflects its power.

01:56:12.140 --> 01:56:14.240
One of the first names active

01:56:14.240 --> 01:56:19.040
in its coinage is an important
tool to write the history.

01:56:19.040 --> 01:56:22.530
Beginning a little before the
middle of the 5th century BC,

01:56:22.530 --> 01:56:26.350
it did appear during
the 3rd century AD.

01:56:26.350 --> 01:56:30.590
Before using coinage,
Tyre like other cities

01:56:30.590 --> 01:56:35.780
in the east used commodity money
or what we call hack silver.

01:56:35.780 --> 01:56:37.340
That means fragments of silver.

01:56:37.340 --> 01:56:41.730
Either pieces of jewelry
or any silver.

01:56:41.730 --> 01:56:43.260
Weight to now the values.

01:56:43.260 --> 01:56:48.140 position:56%
On this you can see that even coins,
Greek coins, were used like that.

01:56:48.140 --> 01:56:51.930
Cut as if it were just
silver [inaudible].

01:56:51.930 --> 01:56:57.280
From the latter half of the 6th
century BC silver coins started

01:56:57.280 --> 01:56:59.450
circulating in the east.

01:56:59.450 --> 01:57:02.980
The oldest coin known was found in
the [inaudible] north of the mouth

01:57:02.980 --> 01:57:10.220
of the [inaudible] river and
was buried around 525-520 BC.

01:57:10.220 --> 01:57:13.970
It only contained foreign
coinage struck

01:57:13.970 --> 01:57:18.620
in Macedonia, Thrace and Cyprus.

01:57:18.620 --> 01:57:21.070
So foreign coins.

01:57:21.070 --> 01:57:24.230
By the end of the 5th century,
[inaudible] bear witness

01:57:24.230 --> 01:57:28.810
to the first strikes of finished
coins from Sidon and Tyre.

01:57:28.810 --> 01:57:33.910
Tyre built a complete monetary
system from the beginning.

01:57:33.910 --> 01:57:40.510
The major denomination was the
shekel, weighing around 13.5 grams.

01:57:40.510 --> 01:57:46.110
And it has a complete succession of
diffusion from the quarter shekel,

01:57:46.110 --> 01:57:49.650
the thirty-second of
shekel and even tiny coins

01:57:49.650 --> 01:57:56.480
that weighted only 0.06 grams, so
really tiny, tiny silver coins.

01:57:56.480 --> 01:58:00.310
During the 4th century
there were even brown coins.

01:58:00.310 --> 01:58:01.840
Compared to the variety

01:58:01.840 --> 01:58:05.330
of the Phoenician city
coinage during the same period,

01:58:05.330 --> 01:58:09.350
Tyre's typology is
limited to two main groups.

01:58:09.350 --> 01:58:15.250
The [inaudible] shows a dolphin
jumping above a wave with a shell

01:58:15.250 --> 01:58:18.510
in the [inaudible] on the rivers.

01:58:18.510 --> 01:58:26.090
[ Inaudible ]

01:58:26.090 --> 01:58:28.650
This first group was spread
during the 5th century.

01:58:28.650 --> 01:58:33.170
On the second group,
the largest by far,

01:58:33.170 --> 01:58:35.710
struck during the 4th century BC.

01:58:35.710 --> 01:58:39.040
A bearded god rides a
winged seahorse to ride

01:58:39.040 --> 01:58:42.350
above waves and on a dolphin.

01:58:42.350 --> 01:58:47.650
The rivers is represented the same
way as in the 5th century group.

01:58:47.650 --> 01:58:52.920
This 4th century group has totally
different profile from the 5th one.

01:58:52.920 --> 01:58:55.650
The Phoenician coins
gain an increasing place

01:58:55.650 --> 01:58:59.500
in circulation during that period.

01:58:59.500 --> 01:59:03.580
They even constituted [inaudible].

01:59:03.580 --> 01:59:09.200
Sidon vastly dominates with nearly
half of [inaudible] and the area

01:59:09.200 --> 01:59:11.320
of circulation that
goes beyond the limits

01:59:11.320 --> 01:59:14.550
of its home regional
zone of influence.

01:59:14.550 --> 01:59:18.880
But Tyre has produced nearly
of 10% of whole specimens

01:59:18.880 --> 01:59:22.610
and its coins circulate
rather widely.

01:59:22.610 --> 01:59:27.150
The image chosen by the Tyrians
too strike their coins provides

01:59:27.150 --> 01:59:29.440
indication of what the city wanted

01:59:29.440 --> 01:59:32.750
to be considered as
its official banner.

01:59:32.750 --> 01:59:37.130
The [inaudible] during the
whole Persian period is a hawk

01:59:37.130 --> 01:59:40.220
with a hawk body wearing
the Egyptian insignia

01:59:40.220 --> 01:59:43.420
of power, a scepter and a flame.

01:59:43.420 --> 01:59:47.430
The Egyptian influence reminds
us of the long-lasting commercial

01:59:47.430 --> 01:59:52.470
and political relationship of
the Phoenician cities with Egypt.

01:59:52.470 --> 01:59:56.150
Which is peculiar to Tyre, but
also sometimes from [inaudible]

01:59:56.150 --> 01:59:59.630
and Sidon is the importance
given to the sea.

01:59:59.630 --> 02:00:03.850
A dolphin jumping above
a wave, the shell,

02:00:03.850 --> 02:00:07.240
the bearded god riding a
seahorse are all related

02:00:07.240 --> 02:00:09.750
to the sea power of Tyre.

02:00:09.750 --> 02:00:14.510
The interesting thing is
that the seahorse is winged.

02:00:14.510 --> 02:00:18.670
It is at the same time
a sea and sky animal.

02:00:18.670 --> 02:00:22.010
Such an [inaudible] which
is completely abnormal

02:00:22.010 --> 02:00:26.600 position:56%
in the Greek context is not puzzling
since the Phoenicians gods can have

02:00:26.600 --> 02:00:30.160
at the same time power
of earth and sky.

02:00:30.160 --> 02:00:35.460
Therefore such an animal
is a convenient mount.

02:00:35.460 --> 02:00:42.150
At the end of 333 BC, Alexander
the great won the battle of Issus

02:00:42.150 --> 02:00:46.490 position:56%
and entered Phoenicia to consolidate
his victory by the diminishing

02:00:46.490 --> 02:00:48.940
of the Mediterranean coast.

02:00:48.940 --> 02:00:52.640
The control of the coastal cities
of Cyprus would guarantee him

02:00:52.640 --> 02:00:55.560
that the Persian fleets
would be kept away

02:00:55.560 --> 02:01:00.620
when it could have [inaudible].

02:01:00.620 --> 02:01:05.410
Raddus, Byblos and Sidon
almost immediately submitted

02:01:05.410 --> 02:01:08.510
to the Macedonian king.

02:01:08.510 --> 02:01:12.070
[ Inaudible ]

02:01:12.070 --> 02:01:16.450
To the considerable
benefit of Alexander.

02:01:16.450 --> 02:01:20.020
He acted quickly, prompting
the [inaudible]

02:01:20.020 --> 02:01:23.240
of the city and their fleets.

02:01:23.240 --> 02:01:25.160
Rapidly thereafter,
fleets of [inaudible]

02:01:25.160 --> 02:01:27.540
and Cyrus joined his camp.

02:01:27.540 --> 02:01:32.850
But Tauria and Giza remained
the only cities to resist.

02:01:32.850 --> 02:01:39.150
The siege of Tyre lasted
from January to July 332 BC.

02:01:39.150 --> 02:01:42.430
However, after he had
conquered the city,

02:01:42.430 --> 02:01:45.040
it seemed that Alexander
didn't change the regime,

02:01:45.040 --> 02:01:47.170
the political regime.

02:01:47.170 --> 02:01:51.290 position:56%
At this part of the resistance,
Tyre kept a king designated by order

02:01:51.290 --> 02:01:55.090
of Alexander from among the
members of the former royal family.

02:01:55.090 --> 02:02:00.830
All the formerly Phoenician cities,
Raddus, Byblos, Sidon and Tyre,

02:02:00.830 --> 02:02:05.330
already issued coins in 333.

02:02:05.330 --> 02:02:08.620
They quickly started to
strike with Alexander's type.

02:02:08.620 --> 02:02:09.980
The head of Heracles.

02:02:09.980 --> 02:02:13.450
Alexander sitting on the throne,

02:02:13.450 --> 02:02:17.120
an eagle in his right
hand on the reverse.

02:02:17.120 --> 02:02:22.120
You can see on that coin, few
Phoenician coins on the reverse

02:02:22.120 --> 02:02:25.470 position:56%
of the coin, just in front of those.

02:02:25.470 --> 02:02:28.450
It is the name of the
reigning Tyrian king.

02:02:28.450 --> 02:02:32.070
It's the first and the last letter

02:02:32.070 --> 02:02:35.630
in Phoenician in the
name of the king.

02:02:35.630 --> 02:02:38.560
Phoenicia was the theater
of an essential [inaudible],

02:02:38.560 --> 02:02:41.000
the monetary history of Alexander.

02:02:41.000 --> 02:02:46.420
The creation of a gold
coinage after July 332.

02:02:46.420 --> 02:02:49.480
And the surrounding of Tyre.

02:02:49.480 --> 02:02:53.180
This will explain the novel
reverse type he chose.

02:02:53.180 --> 02:02:58.110
A [inaudible] holding
what we call a stylus,

02:02:58.110 --> 02:03:01.260
a long tool she's got
on her left shoulder.

02:03:01.260 --> 02:03:03.620
The stylus was the
banner for [inaudible],

02:03:03.620 --> 02:03:06.260
usually taken as a
trophy by the winner.

02:03:06.260 --> 02:03:12.870
And it is here a keen reminder of
his victory on the city of Tyre.

02:03:12.870 --> 02:03:19.820
After Alexander's day in 323 BC,
the [inaudible] was at war due

02:03:19.820 --> 02:03:23.750
to the competition between
Alexander's companion.

02:03:23.750 --> 02:03:27.150
[Inaudible] silver and gold
coins with Alexander's types

02:03:27.150 --> 02:03:30.710
and his name in very large amounts.

02:03:30.710 --> 02:03:33.110
And Tyre was one of the main mints.

02:03:33.110 --> 02:03:35.620
The circulation of these
coins was very wide,

02:03:35.620 --> 02:03:40.010
as far as Alexander's
treks in the east.

02:03:40.010 --> 02:03:48.300
After 301 Phoenicia was part
of a wider region called Syria

02:03:48.300 --> 02:03:52.770
and Phoenicia in the hands of
Ptolemy I, new king of Egypt,

02:03:52.770 --> 02:03:55.710
and former companion
of Alexander the Great.

02:03:55.710 --> 02:03:58.300
He and his son, Ptolemy II,

02:03:58.300 --> 02:04:01.380
completely transformed the
monetary system of the kingdom

02:04:01.380 --> 02:04:05.160
and its dependencies by
introducing a standard [inaudible]

02:04:05.160 --> 02:04:08.600
and the [inaudible] standard
with have been widely used

02:04:08.600 --> 02:04:12.100
as Alexander chose
it for its coinage.

02:04:12.100 --> 02:04:16.500
Ptolemy I created a closed monetary
system with mandatory exchange

02:04:16.500 --> 02:04:19.970
at borders, excluding
all foreign coins.

02:04:19.970 --> 02:04:23.800
In Egypt, the sole mint was
Alexandria, but in Syria

02:04:23.800 --> 02:04:28.310
and Phoenician several mints
were opened, one of them Tyre.

02:04:28.310 --> 02:04:32.500
From 260 the local mints
seem to have supplied most

02:04:32.500 --> 02:04:35.030
of the needs of the area.

02:04:35.030 --> 02:04:40.050 position:56%
Tyre signed its prediction with a
monogram written with Greek letters.

02:04:40.050 --> 02:04:44.060
But you can see the front
of the eagle on the rivers.

02:04:44.060 --> 02:04:45.380
And the club.

02:04:45.380 --> 02:04:52.030
Distinctive attributes of the god
protector of the city, Melqart.

02:04:52.030 --> 02:04:56.030
At the beginning of the second
century, [inaudible] king

02:04:56.030 --> 02:04:59.970
of Syria grabbed Syria
and Phoenicia.

02:04:59.970 --> 02:05:03.060
However, he didn't change
the monetary system.

02:05:03.060 --> 02:05:06.110
It is only at the end
of the second century BC

02:05:06.110 --> 02:05:08.510 position:56%
when the [inaudible] dynasty weakens

02:05:08.510 --> 02:05:12.950
that Tyre started its
own autonomous coinage.

02:05:12.950 --> 02:05:18.410
From 126 BC Tyre issued
this autonomous coinage.

02:05:18.410 --> 02:05:23.910 position:56%
That means coin with its own type
and the name and titles of the city.

02:05:23.910 --> 02:05:26.180 position:56%
From the iconographic point of view,

02:05:26.180 --> 02:05:29.400
the coinage of Tyre
was relatively poor.

02:05:29.400 --> 02:05:33.810
These symbols were most common
during the Persian period.

02:05:33.810 --> 02:05:38.650
[Inaudible] and shells
are secondary symbols.

02:05:38.650 --> 02:05:43.720
A palm tree and Melqart
were all common.

02:05:43.720 --> 02:05:47.860
This god patron of the
city was represented young,

02:05:47.860 --> 02:05:50.600
wearing a laurel reef.

02:05:50.600 --> 02:05:54.650
His identities of use thanks
to the associated club

02:05:54.650 --> 02:05:56.840
that you can see here
on the reverse of the.

02:05:56.840 --> 02:06:00.700
And the appearance of the god
himself with a stout neck,

02:06:00.700 --> 02:06:05.300
strong chin, his head occupying
all the available surface

02:06:05.300 --> 02:06:06.600
of the [inaudible].

02:06:06.600 --> 02:06:13.510
It is a mighty god whose power
comes from its physical strength.

02:06:13.510 --> 02:06:16.040
[ Inaudible ]

02:06:16.040 --> 02:06:20.170
And then a symbol of an
economically reliable coinage.

02:06:20.170 --> 02:06:21.880
A monogram of the city and its name

02:06:21.880 --> 02:06:26.660
in full letters appear
on the reverse.

02:06:26.660 --> 02:06:30.450
Sometimes on other
coins a Atike goddess

02:06:30.450 --> 02:06:33.510
of the city fortune is
represented on autonomous bronze

02:06:33.510 --> 02:06:35.600
with a palm tree on the reverse.

02:06:35.600 --> 02:06:38.200
She's probably the Greek
representation of Serte,

02:06:38.200 --> 02:06:41.480
protective goddess of the city.

02:06:41.480 --> 02:06:43.240
All other deities of city,

02:06:43.240 --> 02:06:47.780
skills and politics are
absent from the coinage.

02:06:47.780 --> 02:06:52.640
A political object, coins bear
the image of gods in charge

02:06:52.640 --> 02:06:57.440
of the political activity
of the community.

02:06:57.440 --> 02:07:01.460
Syria would transfer into
a Roman province in 64 BC.

02:07:01.460 --> 02:07:05.180 position:56%
Syria brought change to the coinage.

02:07:05.180 --> 02:07:08.100
Tyre kept its autonomous
types and its issues

02:07:08.100 --> 02:07:12.740 position:56%
of autonomous silver coins continued
during the first century AD.

02:07:12.740 --> 02:07:15.980
So real change occurred
during the 2nd century AD

02:07:15.980 --> 02:07:19.570
with in particular the
development of references

02:07:19.570 --> 02:07:22.290
to founding myths and local cults.

02:07:22.290 --> 02:07:27.940
The latter were evoked through
a picture [inaudible] positional

02:07:27.940 --> 02:07:31.350 position:56%
[inaudible] objects related to
religious festivals and comparisons.

02:07:31.350 --> 02:07:35.030
Agonistic palms of
victory and so on.

02:07:35.030 --> 02:07:37.040
[ Inaudible ]

02:07:37.040 --> 02:07:39.800
During the Hellenistic
period detailed depictions

02:07:39.800 --> 02:07:41.100
of founding myth.

02:07:41.100 --> 02:07:48.010
So you have here one example
of the coin in the 1st century.

02:07:48.010 --> 02:07:52.580
Here you can see the change
because the reverse --

02:07:52.580 --> 02:07:54.100 position:56%
on the obverse you have the emperor.

02:07:54.100 --> 02:08:00.360
On the reverse you have a very
detailed scene depicting what we

02:08:00.360 --> 02:08:02.590
call the Ambrosian works.

02:08:02.590 --> 02:08:04.240
They were erected in the shrine

02:08:04.240 --> 02:08:07.770
of Heracles Melqart
under an olive tree.

02:08:07.770 --> 02:08:09.660
They were associated
with the foundation

02:08:09.660 --> 02:08:14.530
of the city though the particulars
of the foundation remain unknown.

02:08:14.530 --> 02:08:16.920
They are presented as Talas

02:08:16.920 --> 02:08:20.630
on bronze coins spread
during the 3rd century AD.

02:08:20.630 --> 02:08:23.960
So identification is clear
since the name is written

02:08:23.960 --> 02:08:27.080
on them, Ambrosia Petra.

02:08:27.080 --> 02:08:32.200
Under the exit line, a dog
and a [inaudible] remind us

02:08:32.200 --> 02:08:37.340
of the myth explaining how the
[inaudible] were discovered.

02:08:37.340 --> 02:08:42.180
The famous Tyrian purple was
extracted from this shell.

02:08:43.450 --> 02:08:49.640
Another coin struck between
244 and 249 AD shows Cadmous.

02:08:49.640 --> 02:08:53.020
I'm sorry for the quality, but
this is a very, very rare coin

02:08:53.020 --> 02:08:56.680
and this is the one we've
got in the library in Paris.

02:08:56.680 --> 02:09:00.090
So you can hardly see it
here, but it's very clear

02:09:00.090 --> 02:09:02.350
when you read it directly.

02:09:02.350 --> 02:09:08.150
So it shows Cadmous, king of Tyre
on the right, giving a [inaudible]

02:09:08.150 --> 02:09:10.420
to three men on the left.

02:09:10.420 --> 02:09:13.730
If it's not just with emirs.

02:09:13.730 --> 02:09:18.660
You've got a legion and
there's the exit line.

02:09:18.660 --> 02:09:22.060
Because you have the first
letter of the work Elanos

02:09:22.060 --> 02:09:24.250
at the feet of the three men.

02:09:24.250 --> 02:09:25.550
And there's a man on the right.

02:09:25.550 --> 02:09:27.480
You have cad for Cadmous.

02:09:27.480 --> 02:09:31.590
The scene represents Cadmous
giving the alphabet to the Greeks.

02:09:31.590 --> 02:09:35.230
An eastern heritage for
the Greek civilization.

02:09:35.230 --> 02:09:38.550
Then the 2nd and 3rd
century AD coin designs

02:09:38.550 --> 02:09:42.280
of Tyre are multiple
educational and political.

02:09:42.280 --> 02:09:47.120 position:56%
They contrast strongly with the more
enigmatic sobriety of the issues

02:09:47.120 --> 02:09:49.860
of the Persian and
Hellenistic periods.

02:09:49.860 --> 02:09:52.580
They bear witness to changes
in the religious practice

02:09:52.580 --> 02:09:55.320
from the 2nd century AD in contrast

02:09:55.320 --> 02:09:58.530
to the preceding long-lasting
religious rights.

02:09:58.530 --> 02:10:02.690
They are also a political program
enhancing the central relationships

02:10:02.690 --> 02:10:06.540
and heritage between Phoenicia
and the Greek world at a time

02:10:06.540 --> 02:10:10.080
when Phoenicia was deeply
influenced by Greek culture.

02:10:10.080 --> 02:10:11.710
Thank you.

02:10:11.710 --> 02:10:14.040
[ Applause ]

02:10:14.040 --> 02:10:20.240
&gt;&gt; Thank you, Dr. Duyrat, for
