02:10:20.240 --> 02:10:25.720
Our next presenter is
Dr. Patrick McGovern,

02:10:25.720 --> 02:10:30.540
who direct the biomolecular
archaeology project

02:10:30.540 --> 02:10:34.750
at the University of Pennsylvania
museum in Philadelphia.

02:10:34.750 --> 02:10:38.000
Where he's also an adjunct
professor of anthropology

02:10:38.000 --> 02:10:41.600
and consulting scholar
in the near east section.

02:10:41.600 --> 02:10:45.460
Over the past two years he
has pioneered the exciting

02:10:45.460 --> 02:10:49.920
interdisciplinary field of
biomolecular archaeology

02:10:49.920 --> 02:10:54.510
which is yielding whole new
chapters concerning human ancestry,

02:10:54.510 --> 02:10:58.560
medical practice and ancient
cuisines and beverages.

02:10:58.560 --> 02:11:03.320
He has excavated extensively in
the Middle East, including Lebanon,

02:11:03.320 --> 02:11:06.440
Canaanite and Phoenician Sarafond.

02:11:06.440 --> 02:11:10.990
He is the author of Ancient
Wine: The Search for the Origins

02:11:10.990 --> 02:11:16.470
of Viniculture, published
in 2003-04.

02:11:16.470 --> 02:11:20.940
And most recently Uncorking
the Past: The Quest for Wine,

02:11:20.940 --> 02:11:24.210
Beer and other Alcoholic Beverages.

02:11:24.210 --> 02:11:28.510
Without further ado,
Dr. Patrick McGovern.

02:11:28.510 --> 02:11:31.040
[ Applause ]

02:11:31.040 --> 02:11:32.340
&gt;&gt; Dr. Patrick McGovern: Thank you.

02:11:32.340 --> 02:11:33.640
I'm very happy to be here.

02:11:33.640 --> 02:11:36.560
And I'm thankful to the Tyre
committee for inviting me to talk

02:11:36.560 --> 02:11:39.120
about two of the technological

02:11:39.120 --> 02:11:42.300
and artistic creations
of the Phoenicians.

02:11:42.300 --> 02:11:45.100
I mean, the Phoenicians are
responsible for a great deal.

02:11:45.100 --> 02:11:46.480
We've heard about the alphabet,

02:11:46.480 --> 02:11:49.730
we've heard about some
coinage, ship building.

02:11:49.730 --> 02:11:52.160
There's metalworking, glass making.

02:11:52.160 --> 02:11:55.880
And I'm going to talk about
royal purple and wine.

02:11:55.880 --> 02:11:59.820
My first experience in
archaeology was actually in Lebanon

02:11:59.820 --> 02:12:03.250
at a site not too far
from Tyre called Surepta,

02:12:03.250 --> 02:12:06.600
or Sarafond which is
only about 11 kilometers

02:12:06.600 --> 02:12:09.350
as the crow flies north of Tyre.

02:12:09.350 --> 02:12:12.660
So I have a great affinity
for Lebanon

02:12:12.660 --> 02:12:15.260
and what it really represents.

02:12:15.260 --> 02:12:20.250
Because I think it took technology
and art and transferred them

02:12:20.250 --> 02:12:24.540
across the Mediterranean and
eventually to the whole world.

02:12:24.540 --> 02:12:29.650
So it's a very special country
and I think we need to find

02:12:29.650 --> 02:12:30.950
out a great deal more about it.

02:12:30.950 --> 02:12:35.870
I mean, I'm really saddened by
the events since the civil war

02:12:35.870 --> 02:12:38.820
and so forth, and how difficult
it is to excavate in that country.

02:12:38.820 --> 02:12:43.350
But I think it holds secrets
that we really can't imagine.

02:12:43.350 --> 02:12:45.620
I think architecture too.

02:12:45.620 --> 02:12:48.800
We've heard about the Tyre temple
and we're going to hear more

02:12:48.800 --> 02:12:50.360
about that this afternoon.

02:12:50.360 --> 02:12:57.840
So I think architecture and temple
worship, religion, theater, music.

02:12:57.840 --> 02:13:01.930
There's a whole series of
contributions that the Phoenicians

02:13:01.930 --> 02:13:06.410 position:56%
and the Canaanites, the predecessors
of Phoenicians, contributed.

02:13:06.410 --> 02:13:10.990
So I'm going to talk about
royal purple as a good example,

02:13:10.990 --> 02:13:14.830
or Tyrian purple we can call it.

02:13:14.830 --> 02:13:19.430
Because there's a Greek
myth you could say

02:13:19.430 --> 02:13:23.510
that the Phoenicians are the ones
who developed purple initially

02:13:23.510 --> 02:13:25.190
or even back to the Canaanites.

02:13:25.190 --> 02:13:30.000
And that the words for
Phoenicia and Canaan do derive

02:13:30.000 --> 02:13:32.850
from ancient words for purple.

02:13:32.850 --> 02:13:37.140
So this is very integral to the
Canaanites and the Phoenicians.

02:13:37.140 --> 02:13:38.770
Now here we see this myth

02:13:38.770 --> 02:13:45.790
of Heracles walking along the
shore of Tyre with his dog.

02:13:45.790 --> 02:13:49.250
And the dog is biting
into different shells.

02:13:49.250 --> 02:13:53.790 position:56%
And this is the Greek idea of how
maybe it could have been discovered.

02:13:53.790 --> 02:14:05.030
The dog bites into a murex shell
which has the purple dye gland.

02:14:05.030 --> 02:14:07.130
And I'll show that to
you a little bit later.

02:14:07.130 --> 02:14:13.040
And that inspires Heracles
then to take the dye and make

02:14:13.040 --> 02:14:17.620 position:56%
up textiles for his consort goddess.

02:14:17.620 --> 02:14:22.460
And so begins the royal
purple dye making.

02:14:22.460 --> 02:14:26.900
But we have more definitive
archaeological evidence.

02:14:26.900 --> 02:14:33.130
And it comes from the site of
Surepta where I worked in 1974

02:14:33.130 --> 02:14:37.700
as Israeli jets pounded
the local Palestinian camp.

02:14:37.700 --> 02:14:43.070
You had to be very intrepid to
work at Surepta in those days.

02:14:43.070 --> 02:14:45.660
And Leila Badre can attest to that

02:14:45.660 --> 02:14:47.890
because she was there
at the same time.

02:14:47.890 --> 02:14:52.980
And it is a site that's
located between Tyre and Sidon,

02:14:52.980 --> 02:14:55.230
about halfway in between.

02:14:55.230 --> 02:14:59.920
And when they started getting
down into the late bronze,

02:14:59.920 --> 02:15:05.080
early iron age levels, this is
from about 1300 BC to 1100 BC.

02:15:05.080 --> 02:15:10.720
This is one of the few homeland
Canaanite/Phoenician sites

02:15:10.720 --> 02:15:12.020
that has been excavated.

02:15:12.020 --> 02:15:13.770
Now Sidon is getting
a lot more information

02:15:13.770 --> 02:15:16.800
and we hope that Tyre will as well.

02:15:16.800 --> 02:15:19.690
We came down onto an
industrial area.

02:15:19.690 --> 02:15:22.020
This is done by the University
of Pennsylvania Museum

02:15:22.020 --> 02:15:27.320
under James Pritchard who some
of you may know or have heard of.

02:15:27.320 --> 02:15:30.390
We started finding Canaanite jars.

02:15:30.390 --> 02:15:33.650
I was a graduate student at
this time, so I was working

02:15:33.650 --> 02:15:36.870
on the pottery and going
through it very carefully.

02:15:36.870 --> 02:15:41.930
And you'll see here that this
industrial area had kilns

02:15:41.930 --> 02:15:43.450
for making the pottery.

02:15:43.450 --> 02:15:50.100
But in addition it also had purple
colored shards on the inside

02:15:50.100 --> 02:15:52.120
of amphoras or Canaanite jars.

02:15:52.120 --> 02:15:57.400
And also processing
vats for making the dye.

02:15:57.400 --> 02:16:02.380 position:56%
And when we saw these purple colored
shards, our immediate instincts was

02:16:02.380 --> 02:16:07.580
that these were possibly
real Tyrian purple.

02:16:07.580 --> 02:16:12.580
Now they could be from an inorganic
coloring like manganese or iron.

02:16:12.580 --> 02:16:15.740
But if they were the
real Tyrian royal purple,

02:16:15.740 --> 02:16:18.340
they would be an organic compound.

02:16:18.340 --> 02:16:22.630
And we had just started in
on doing organic analyses

02:16:22.630 --> 02:16:24.390
at the University of
Pennsylvania museum.

02:16:24.390 --> 02:16:28.040
First I'd work on pottery
and glass and so forth.

02:16:28.040 --> 02:16:30.340
And then I was always very
interested in organic chemistry.

02:16:30.340 --> 02:16:34.160
And we were just developing the
techniques 20 years ago to be able

02:16:34.160 --> 02:16:40.190
to analyze organic compounds and
see what the ancient dye might be

02:16:40.190 --> 02:16:42.260
or ancient food or whatever.

02:16:42.260 --> 02:16:47.930
And so this is a very small shard
that we worked with from Surepta

02:16:47.930 --> 02:16:50.190
that had the purple
color on the inside.

02:16:50.190 --> 02:16:52.410
It was from an amphora.

02:16:52.410 --> 02:16:55.310
And for those who are
chemically challenged among you,

02:16:55.310 --> 02:16:57.060
I'm not going to give
you all the details.

02:16:57.060 --> 02:17:01.350
We've published extensively
on the chemical results.

02:17:01.350 --> 02:17:05.060
And we have used spectroscopic
techniques.

02:17:05.060 --> 02:17:07.830
Mass spectrometry works very well.

02:17:07.830 --> 02:17:12.850
And there's a particular
vat dye test that you can do

02:17:12.850 --> 02:17:15.910
that almost certainly
shows that we're dealing

02:17:15.910 --> 02:17:19.670
with what's called
6-6-prime dibromoindigotin.

02:17:19.670 --> 02:17:22.220
It's an indigo compound
that has two bromines,

02:17:22.220 --> 02:17:24.160
one on each side of the molecule.

02:17:24.160 --> 02:17:26.690 position:56%
And the indigo of course gives blue.

02:17:26.690 --> 02:17:30.330
But if you put the bromines on, it
switches the color over to purple.

02:17:30.330 --> 02:17:33.680
And there's a lot of
fascinating details about this dye

02:17:33.680 --> 02:17:37.220
and I'll refer you again to some
of the articles I've written about.

02:17:37.220 --> 02:17:41.500
It comes from a gland,
as I mentioned,

02:17:41.500 --> 02:17:45.180
in the murex mollusk that's
found in the Mediterranean.

02:17:45.180 --> 02:17:47.030
There's three different species.

02:17:47.030 --> 02:17:54.650
And this is an example where you
can see it's a yellowish fluid

02:17:54.650 --> 02:17:57.890
that comes out of this gland,
called the hypobranchial gland.

02:17:57.890 --> 02:18:01.370
And when it's exposed to light
and air, it changes to purple.

02:18:01.370 --> 02:18:04.450
So it's something that people
could have discovered quite easily.

02:18:04.450 --> 02:18:08.180
And there's related species of
mollusks all over the world.

02:18:08.180 --> 02:18:11.500
So the ancient Mayans, Chinese,

02:18:11.500 --> 02:18:15.090
Incans and so forth
discovered related species.

02:18:15.090 --> 02:18:18.280
And if you're using it as
a food source and you start

02:18:18.280 --> 02:18:21.450
to handle the Murex, you're
going to get it on your fingers.

02:18:21.450 --> 02:18:24.560
And it is a very fast dye.

02:18:24.560 --> 02:18:26.550
It's very hard to remove.

02:18:26.550 --> 02:18:30.410
So people would have realized
it was a good textile dye

02:18:30.410 --> 02:18:33.080
and started using it
for that purpose.

02:18:33.080 --> 02:18:37.410
Okay, so that is a little
glimpse of the royal purple.

02:18:37.410 --> 02:18:39.260
You know, there's lots
more I could say about it.

02:18:39.260 --> 02:18:42.320
But now I want to move
on to another luxury good

02:18:42.320 --> 02:18:44.390
which also has technological

02:18:44.390 --> 02:18:48.210
and artistic ramifications,
and that's ancient wine.

02:18:48.210 --> 02:18:49.730
Which I've written a book about.

02:18:49.730 --> 02:18:52.450
So you're welcome to ask me about.

02:18:52.450 --> 02:18:54.440
And I also hope we'll be having --

02:18:54.440 --> 02:18:59.310 position:56%
on that first slide at the beginning
I showed a view of the Baca valley

02:18:59.310 --> 02:19:03.630
where winemaking has probably
gone on for thousands of years.

02:19:03.630 --> 02:19:09.630
Now this is a map that shows in
purple, appropriately enough,

02:19:09.630 --> 02:19:12.460
and I'm glad that some of
you are wearing purple today.

02:19:12.460 --> 02:19:17.710
Where the wild grapevine,
the wild Eurasian grapevine,

02:19:17.710 --> 02:19:20.300
vitis vinifera, grows today.

02:19:20.300 --> 02:19:22.880
And we think that basically
it's the same region.

02:19:22.880 --> 02:19:27.570
And you'll notice that the
area -- well before I do that,

02:19:27.570 --> 02:19:30.580
you'll notice that Lebanon is

02:19:30.580 --> 02:19:35.920
at the most southerly extent
of the wild grape vine.

02:19:35.920 --> 02:19:42.020
So when humans came out of
Africa say 100,000 years ago

02:19:42.020 --> 02:19:46.300
and they crossed over the Sinai
and up into the near east,

02:19:46.300 --> 02:19:52.000
they would see the grape for
the first time in Lebanon.

02:19:52.000 --> 02:19:58.510
And I think that they would be
quite interested in this fruit.

02:19:58.510 --> 02:20:01.310
[ Laughter ]

02:20:01.310 --> 02:20:04.190
And so they would maybe
start experimenting with it.

02:20:04.190 --> 02:20:07.610
But now so far we have a
project now up in Georgia

02:20:07.610 --> 02:20:12.630
in the Caucuses looking at the
earliest evidence for winemaking

02:20:12.630 --> 02:20:16.440
and for the domestication
of the grapevine.

02:20:16.440 --> 02:20:21.060
It appears that the
domestication occurs somewhere

02:20:21.060 --> 02:20:22.820
in the mountainous
region of the near east.

02:20:22.820 --> 02:20:25.640 position:56%
It could be up in the Caucuses, but
it could also be near eastern Turkey

02:20:25.640 --> 02:20:28.690
and the Taurus mountains,
over to the Zagros mountains.

02:20:28.690 --> 02:20:31.280
But even down into Lebanon.

02:20:31.280 --> 02:20:37.620 position:56%
And unfortunately we've had no real
gathering of grapes and DNA analyses

02:20:37.620 --> 02:20:43.280 position:56%
in Lebanon to test you know, whether
it could have first merged there.

02:20:43.280 --> 02:20:48.240
But we do know that the Canaanites

02:20:48.240 --> 02:20:50.320
and then the Phoenicians
are very much involved

02:20:50.320 --> 02:20:54.160
in spreading the wine
culture, wherever it emerges.

02:20:54.160 --> 02:20:59.140
And by wine culture mean
something like Lebanon today,

02:20:59.140 --> 02:21:01.250
where wine can become very much --

02:21:01.250 --> 02:21:03.280
of course you have
Ararack and what have you.

02:21:03.280 --> 02:21:06.840
Wine can become very
central to the economy,

02:21:06.840 --> 02:21:08.840
the social life, the religion.

02:21:08.840 --> 02:21:14.820 position:56%
And sort of embeds itself right into
the culture in a very profound way.

02:21:14.820 --> 02:21:20.480
But we do see in later periods
how this wine culture then spread

02:21:20.480 --> 02:21:24.740
principally from the
Canaanite Phoenician area.

02:21:24.740 --> 02:21:29.860 position:56%
So around 4000 BC -- we probably had
the emergence of the wine culture

02:21:29.860 --> 02:21:33.390
around 6000 BC in the
mountainous areas of the near east.

02:21:33.390 --> 02:21:37.010
Then by 4000 BC it had spread
down to the Jordan valley.

02:21:37.010 --> 02:21:39.940
And we have grape seeds
of domesticated grape

02:21:39.940 --> 02:21:42.230
that have been found
about that time.

02:21:42.230 --> 02:21:44.450
And then ultimately
it goes on to Egypt

02:21:44.450 --> 02:21:48.390
where you'll notice Egypt did
not have the wild grapevine.

02:21:48.390 --> 02:21:51.930
You had to bring in the
domesticated grapevine.

02:21:51.930 --> 02:21:53.820
And who did that?

02:21:53.820 --> 02:21:55.890
Well it was the Canaanites
and the Phoenicians.

02:21:55.890 --> 02:21:58.890
And I'll show you a few more
slides to illustrate that.

02:21:58.890 --> 02:22:04.240
But then the Phoenicians also
took the grape and wine culture

02:22:04.240 --> 02:22:05.660
across the Mediterranean.

02:22:05.660 --> 02:22:10.820
And we've done a lot of analyses
now on vessels from Crete

02:22:10.820 --> 02:22:15.100
and other parts of even the
western Mediterranean that show

02:22:15.100 --> 02:22:21.850
that at least by 2200 BC
wine was being made on Crete.

02:22:21.850 --> 02:22:26.180
So the Greeks are absorbing
the wine culture.

02:22:26.180 --> 02:22:31.540
And the earliest shipwreck in
the Mediterranean from Uluburun,

02:22:31.540 --> 02:22:33.900
which is just off the
southern coast of Turkey,

02:22:33.900 --> 02:22:39.680
dated about 1350 BC,
is a Canaanite ship.

02:22:39.680 --> 02:22:44.610
So here the Canaanites were
transporting all sorts of goods

02:22:44.610 --> 02:22:47.300
and spreading out into
the Mediterranean,

02:22:47.300 --> 02:22:49.660
establishing colonies and so forth.

02:22:49.660 --> 02:22:52.440
And you'll see there
are some amphoras.

02:22:52.440 --> 02:22:54.430
This is a reconstructed view

02:22:54.430 --> 02:22:57.300
of what the Uluburun shipwreck
would have looked like.

02:22:57.300 --> 02:23:03.020 position:56%
Because a lot of the goods were
spread out along a very steep slope.

02:23:03.020 --> 02:23:08.700 position:56%
So they tried to figure out what the
weight, the ballast would have been

02:23:08.700 --> 02:23:12.610
on certain parts of the ship and
the different sizes of amphoras.

02:23:12.610 --> 02:23:17.210
And we are just publishing
an article that shows

02:23:17.210 --> 02:23:20.000
that they had wine
on board this ship.

02:23:20.000 --> 02:23:24.030
This has been sometimes
controversial.

02:23:24.030 --> 02:23:26.040
[ Laughter ]

02:23:26.040 --> 02:23:28.390
I think if you're Canaanites you
have wine on board your ship.

02:23:28.390 --> 02:23:35.400
And then we did an analysis of
other amphoras that were found

02:23:35.400 --> 02:23:42.080
in shipwrecks from the 8th
century BC off of Ashkelon.

02:23:42.080 --> 02:23:46.920
And they were carrying an
enormous number of amphoras.

02:23:46.920 --> 02:23:52.150
This is a photograph by
remotely operated submersible.

02:23:52.150 --> 02:23:55.760
But it showed hundreds
of amphoras in the ships.

02:23:55.760 --> 02:23:58.160
And there were two ships.

02:23:58.160 --> 02:24:03.540
And they were given the ships
Tanit, and Elissa or Dido.

02:24:03.540 --> 02:24:08.150
And they were carrying,
according to our analysis, wine.

02:24:08.150 --> 02:24:11.880
Now the wine in this case
also has a resin in it.

02:24:11.880 --> 02:24:14.610
It could be pine resin
or terabinth resin.

02:24:14.610 --> 02:24:17.990
And that helps to keep
it from spoiling.

02:24:17.990 --> 02:24:22.680
So they then went out across to
Greece and Crete as I mentioned.

02:24:22.680 --> 02:24:27.650
And I think ultimately, according
to another article that we've done

02:24:27.650 --> 02:24:31.070
in the proceedings from the
National Academy of Sciences --

02:24:31.070 --> 02:24:33.850
and these are available on my
website if you're interested.

02:24:33.850 --> 02:24:36.970 position:56%
The French ultimately got winemaking

02:24:36.970 --> 02:24:40.720
and the wine culture
through the Etruscans.

02:24:40.720 --> 02:24:44.410
This occurs around the
8th, 7th, 6th century BC.

02:24:44.410 --> 02:24:46.650
But my belief, and I
think it will be shown

02:24:46.650 --> 02:24:49.180
as more shipwrecks are excavated,

02:24:49.180 --> 02:24:52.010
is that the Phoenicians
are really the ones

02:24:52.010 --> 02:24:53.640
that transferred the wine culture

02:24:53.640 --> 02:24:56.480
and the domesticated
grapevine to the Etruscans.

02:24:56.480 --> 02:24:58.840
And then ultimately to the French.

02:24:58.840 --> 02:25:04.460
So the beginnings of winemaking in
France go back to the Phoenicians,

02:25:04.460 --> 02:25:06.960
which is not all that surprising.

02:25:06.960 --> 02:25:11.510
I hope I'm not upsetting anybody.

02:25:11.510 --> 02:25:14.250
[ Applause ]

02:25:14.250 --> 02:25:18.110
And just to give you
some examples from Egypt

02:25:18.110 --> 02:25:21.700 position:56%
of how important the Canaanites were
there, one of the earliest tombs

02:25:21.700 --> 02:25:30.020
of a pharaoh is one of Scorpion
I at Abidos around 3150 BC.

02:25:30.020 --> 02:25:37.080
And he had 700 jars of
wine, about 4,500 liters

02:25:37.080 --> 02:25:39.430
of wine put into his tomb.

02:25:39.430 --> 02:25:42.180
So the king was buried on a bed

02:25:42.180 --> 02:25:44.700
on the back there with
his mace in hand.

02:25:44.700 --> 02:25:48.340 position:56%
And then there was beer and bread
and so forth in the middle chambers.

02:25:48.340 --> 02:25:52.020
And then there were three sort
of wine cellars, you know,

02:25:52.020 --> 02:25:53.830
stacked up with these jars.

02:25:53.830 --> 02:25:58.100
And we were able show that
this again was a resinated wine

02:25:58.100 --> 02:25:59.730
that had figs put into it.

02:25:59.730 --> 02:26:03.770
It also had thyme and savory.

02:26:03.770 --> 02:26:06.610
You were eating zatar this morning.

02:26:06.610 --> 02:26:08.790
We have shown that some
of the earliest wine --

02:26:08.790 --> 02:26:11.390
and this was probably, according
to the neutron activation analyses

02:26:11.390 --> 02:26:15.460
of the pottery, it comes from
the Jordan valley in this case.

02:26:15.460 --> 02:26:17.410
And the surrounding hill country

02:26:17.410 --> 02:26:20.210
where the wine was
then exported to Egypt.

02:26:20.210 --> 02:26:23.330
And that gave the Egyptians
the impetus to set

02:26:23.330 --> 02:26:28.440
up their own wine industry
around 3000 BC.

02:26:28.440 --> 02:26:30.500
And we have these beautiful
depictions of course

02:26:30.500 --> 02:26:32.250
as probably some of
you have seen in Egypt

02:26:32.250 --> 02:26:33.860
of how the winemaking was done.

02:26:33.860 --> 02:26:37.320
Well, this is a pretty
sophisticated system that goes back

02:26:37.320 --> 02:26:38.850 position:56%
to the beginning of the old kingdom.

02:26:38.850 --> 02:26:41.160
I mean, I'm showing a fresco
here from the new kingdom.

02:26:41.160 --> 02:26:44.170
But there's equal examples
from the old kingdom.

02:26:44.170 --> 02:26:49.060
It shows how they were able
to have arbors or pergolas

02:26:49.060 --> 02:26:52.940
with grapes growing up
high, which blocks the sun.

02:26:52.940 --> 02:26:55.590
Because you're in a very hot
climate in the Nile delta.

02:26:55.590 --> 02:26:59.020
So it's the Canaanites who are
transplanting the grapevine

02:26:59.020 --> 02:27:03.170
to the delta, setting up the
winemaking industry there.

02:27:03.170 --> 02:27:05.970
And using very advanced
horticultural methods.

02:27:05.970 --> 02:27:08.850
They even had irrigation
of single plants we see

02:27:08.850 --> 02:27:10.510
in some of the illustrations.

02:27:10.510 --> 02:27:15.040
And of course doing the stomping
operation, putting it into jars,

02:27:15.040 --> 02:27:20.010 position:56%
knowing how to seal it, how to do
the fermentation and how to keep it.

02:27:20.010 --> 02:27:27.960
And this influence
ultimately comes from Lebanon.

02:27:27.960 --> 02:27:32.000
We know from the textile evidence
of the Greeks and so forth

02:27:32.000 --> 02:27:36.350
that Lebanese wine, especially
Bybline or Byblos wine,

02:27:36.350 --> 02:27:40.960 position:56%
was renowned in the ancient world as
being the equal of any Greek wine.

02:27:40.960 --> 02:27:44.220
They said it was comparable
to the Lesbos wine.

02:27:44.220 --> 02:27:49.110
And it was very much a part
of ceremonies in Lebanon.

02:27:49.110 --> 02:27:54.030
We have from the Ras Shamra texts
that they had special worship

02:27:54.030 --> 02:27:58.010
and meals and ceremonies
for the ancestors,

02:27:58.010 --> 02:28:00.740
which features lots of wine.

02:28:00.740 --> 02:28:06.190
Which also the gods Baal and
Hel sometimes overindulged in.

02:28:06.190 --> 02:28:11.990
So we've got a culture there that
is definitely a wine-based culture.

02:28:11.990 --> 02:28:14.580 position:56%
And yet we know very little about it

02:28:14.580 --> 02:28:18.520
because we have not done
any analyses of vessels

02:28:18.520 --> 02:28:24.730
from the homeland of Phoenician
area that we can really rely on.

02:28:24.730 --> 02:28:29.180
Or at least there might be some
in progress that suggest Cartamum,

02:28:29.180 --> 02:28:31.450
but I kind of wonder about that.

02:28:31.450 --> 02:28:36.370
But we've got these spectacular
vases, the mushroom-lipped juglet

02:28:36.370 --> 02:28:39.830
and the amphora and so forth
that need to be analyzed.

02:28:39.830 --> 02:28:46.390
And on this particular
sarcophagus of Hiram of Byblos,

02:28:46.390 --> 02:28:49.270
we see him holding
a cup in his hand.

02:28:49.270 --> 02:28:51.090
And what was that cup filled with?

02:28:51.090 --> 02:28:53.620
Well, we would think
it would be with wine.

02:28:53.620 --> 02:28:55.950 position:56%
But we still have yet to prove this.

02:28:55.950 --> 02:28:59.170
And we really need a lot
more work and protection

02:28:59.170 --> 02:29:02.390
of the antiquities in Lebanon.

02:29:02.390 --> 02:29:04.030
Thank you.

02:29:04.030 --> 02:29:06.040
[ Applause ]

02:29:06.040 --> 02:29:09.750
&gt;&gt; Thank you very much,
Dr. McGovern.

02:29:09.750 --> 02:29:15.000
Our next speaker is
Dr. Peter Von Dommelen.

02:29:15.000 --> 02:29:20.170
He's an archaeologist studying
cross cultural interactions

02:29:20.170 --> 02:29:24.050
and colonial connections in
the ancient Mediterranean.

02:29:24.050 --> 02:29:27.270
Especially in the Phoenician
and Punic worlds.

02:29:27.270 --> 02:29:32.320
His research concerns topics like
migration, rule of households,

02:29:32.320 --> 02:29:37.280
ancient agriculture and landscapes
in the western Mediterranean

02:29:37.280 --> 02:29:40.730
in both ancient and
more recent times.

02:29:40.730 --> 02:29:47.000
They also structured long-term
field work and ceramic studies

02:29:47.000 --> 02:29:50.600
on the island of Sardinia, Italy.

02:29:50.600 --> 02:29:54.540
He's the Dukowski family professor
of archaeology and professor

02:29:54.540 --> 02:29:59.220
of anthropology at Brown University
in Providence, Rhode Island.

02:29:59.220 --> 02:30:07.110 position:56%
And has held visiting professorships
at University of Valencia in Spain,

02:30:07.110 --> 02:30:11.070
[Spanish name] in Spain
and Cagliari in Italy.

02:30:11.070 --> 02:30:16.490 position:56%
Recent publications have appeared
in the Journal of Roman archaeology,

02:30:16.490 --> 02:30:22.250
[foreign name] and the Annual
Review of Anthropology.

02:30:22.250 --> 02:30:29.470
They also include rural
landscapes of the Punic world,

02:30:29.470 --> 02:30:35.290
and the Cambridge prehistory of the
bronze and iron age Mediterranean.

02:30:35.290 --> 02:30:37.740
He also serves as co-editor
of the Journal

02:30:37.740 --> 02:30:42.330
of Mediterranean Archaeology
and World Archaeology.

02:30:42.330 --> 02:30:45.510
Dr. Dommelen.

02:30:45.510 --> 02:30:49.050
[ Applause ]

02:30:49.050 --> 02:30:50.350
&gt;&gt; Dr. Peter Dommelen:
Thank you very much

02:30:50.350 --> 02:30:51.650
for your kind introduction.

02:30:51.650 --> 02:30:55.190
And of course also, my thanks
to the committee for Tyre.

02:30:55.190 --> 02:30:58.700 position:56%
Because it's an honor to speak
here, but also a great pleasure here

02:30:58.700 --> 02:31:02.090
to talk to you about
Phoenician archaeology.

02:31:02.090 --> 02:31:05.880
As you heard in the
introduction, I'm an archaeologist

02:31:05.880 --> 02:31:08.470
and working particularly
on cultural interaction.

02:31:08.470 --> 02:31:12.140
So what happens when people
migrate, go and work somewhere else

02:31:12.140 --> 02:31:14.230
and how they learn
things from others,

02:31:14.230 --> 02:31:16.350
how they start doing
things in different ways?

02:31:16.350 --> 02:31:20.000
And in the process sort of come
up with novel ways of doing that

02:31:20.000 --> 02:31:22.180
or consuming things as well.

02:31:22.180 --> 02:31:27.980
And most of my research over
the past 25 years has been

02:31:27.980 --> 02:31:29.540
involving Phoenicians.

02:31:29.540 --> 02:31:34.710
But without going into Lebanon
myself, which is still a place

02:31:34.710 --> 02:31:36.770
where I have to go, I must confess.

02:31:36.770 --> 02:31:39.390
Because all of my work in
fact has been concentrated

02:31:39.390 --> 02:31:42.990
in the west Mediterranean and
that is what I will be speaking

02:31:42.990 --> 02:31:44.290
about here.

02:31:44.290 --> 02:31:46.910
So it's under the heading
of material connections.

02:31:46.910 --> 02:31:51.380
Because the fate of Tyre is, as
we've heard and as we've seen

02:31:51.380 --> 02:31:55.000
to some extent or a large
extent, based on the city itself.

02:31:55.000 --> 02:31:56.960
But not just and not only that,

02:31:56.960 --> 02:31:58.970
but it's also on the
overseas connections,

02:31:58.970 --> 02:32:03.610
what Tyrians were doing
overseas and what they were

02:32:03.610 --> 02:32:06.350
up to in those faraway places.

02:32:06.350 --> 02:32:10.410
And archaeology is actually crucial
for understanding these things.

02:32:10.410 --> 02:32:13.510
Archaeology is about stuff,
about things that you find,

02:32:13.510 --> 02:32:16.700
and hence they make up
these material connections.

02:32:16.700 --> 02:32:22.870
Because this is obviously a huge
and vast topic, I'm only going

02:32:22.870 --> 02:32:26.010
to be touching on a
couple of points today

02:32:26.010 --> 02:32:27.810
because of the constraints of time.

02:32:27.810 --> 02:32:32.740 position:56%
And what I want to highlight is to
take you on a kind of whirlwind tour

02:32:32.740 --> 02:32:36.320 position:56%
across the Mediterranean and
highlight some of the rapid advances

02:32:36.320 --> 02:32:39.720
that the discipline of
archaeology has been making

02:32:39.720 --> 02:32:41.020
in this regard as well.

02:32:41.020 --> 02:32:43.580
And really in sort of recent years.

02:32:43.580 --> 02:32:46.450 position:56%
And I'm beginning here straight away
with this sort of introductory slide

02:32:46.450 --> 02:32:49.490 position:56%
which I'm not going to say much more
about, other than you're looking

02:32:49.490 --> 02:32:52.850
at this wonderful view, which is on
the island or just off the island

02:32:52.850 --> 02:32:58.740
of Sardinia where the peninsula in
the background is the colonial site

02:32:58.740 --> 02:33:01.190
of Bitia, southeast Sardinia.

02:33:01.190 --> 02:33:03.840
And we're looking at
it from the Tophart,

02:33:03.840 --> 02:33:07.240
which is one of those weird
sites that were created

02:33:07.240 --> 02:33:10.990
in the wester Phoenician
colonial world.

02:33:10.990 --> 02:33:14.220
And again, one of the things -- I
don't have time to go into detail,

02:33:14.220 --> 02:33:18.890
but we might touch
on it here or there.

02:33:18.890 --> 02:33:21.510
Tyre and its overseas connection.

02:33:21.510 --> 02:33:24.180
Because it's not just archaeology

02:33:24.180 --> 02:33:25.750
that gives us information
about these.

02:33:25.750 --> 02:33:29.120
Of course, as we've already seen in
previous talks, there's all sorts

02:33:29.120 --> 02:33:34.170
of iconographic sources,
illustrations of various kinds

02:33:34.170 --> 02:33:39.600
as we see here in these
reliefs or in this bronze plate.

02:33:39.600 --> 02:33:45.210
That was originally fixed on a gate
in Balawat in neo-Syrian period.

02:33:45.210 --> 02:33:48.720
And of course there's all
kinds of literary sources.

02:33:48.720 --> 02:33:53.160 position:56%
But even when we look at these
epigraphic and iconographic sources,

02:33:53.160 --> 02:33:58.160
we can see very well that
they show us lots of stuff,

02:33:58.160 --> 02:33:59.730
lots of things in the archaeology.

02:33:59.730 --> 02:34:05.780
We see trees, timber being
transported in forms of tribute

02:34:05.780 --> 02:34:07.290
that we just heard a lot about,

02:34:07.290 --> 02:34:10.250
these Canaan amphorae
being transported.

02:34:10.250 --> 02:34:13.420
And to some extent the amphorae
themselves, the clay vessels.

02:34:13.420 --> 02:34:15.340
But of course it wasn't
just about the vessels.

02:34:15.340 --> 02:34:18.370
It was clearly, as we heard,
all about the contents of them.

02:34:18.370 --> 02:34:20.230
So there's a lot of these.

02:34:20.230 --> 02:34:23.560
Even if we look at nonmaterial
sources, it's sort of the material

02:34:23.560 --> 02:34:27.760
that sort of makes up those
connections that's paramount there.

02:34:27.760 --> 02:34:30.070
But with archaeology we can
actually do something more.

02:34:30.070 --> 02:34:31.640
And that's more what
I want to talk about,

02:34:31.640 --> 02:34:33.300
sort of these material connections.

02:34:33.300 --> 02:34:35.870
They give us insight
in everyday life.

02:34:35.870 --> 02:34:40.160
We can talk about what was life in
those colonial oversea settlements?

02:34:40.160 --> 02:34:41.890
And what were people up there --

02:34:41.890 --> 02:34:45.280
how were they building a
life in faraway places?

02:34:45.280 --> 02:34:47.710
So the places I want to
sort of briefly touch

02:34:47.710 --> 02:34:49.490
on here is of course Carthage.

02:34:49.490 --> 02:34:52.770 position:56%
How could we not talk about Carthage
when we talk about the west?

02:34:52.770 --> 02:34:55.240
But as you can see there the
concentration on the island

02:34:55.240 --> 02:34:57.850
of Sardinia, which has all
to do with that as a place

02:34:57.850 --> 02:35:00.170
where I conduct my fieldwork.

02:35:00.170 --> 02:35:04.170
But very important of course
is the Spanish peninsula,

02:35:04.170 --> 02:35:06.620
the Iberian peninsula
where we haven't heard much

02:35:06.620 --> 02:35:07.920
about so far today.

02:35:07.920 --> 02:35:12.220
But the city Cassis situated
just outside the Mediterranean,

02:35:12.220 --> 02:35:13.600
on the Atlantic shores.

02:35:13.600 --> 02:35:21.960
That is a key element of this
Phoenician/Tyrian expansion.

02:35:21.960 --> 02:35:23.840
So first Carthage.

02:35:23.840 --> 02:35:28.860
Carthage, famously founded by Dido
Elissa, and we'll hear much more

02:35:28.860 --> 02:35:32.430
about it in a later talk as
I gather from the program.

02:35:32.430 --> 02:35:36.820
And we have from our literary
sources, historical sources,

02:35:36.820 --> 02:35:40.540
traditional foundation
date of 814 BCE.

02:35:40.540 --> 02:35:43.990 position:56%
And there has been a long discussion
whether that would be reliable.

02:35:43.990 --> 02:35:45.600
Because most of the
archaeology was coming

02:35:45.600 --> 02:35:47.450
up with somewhat younger dates.

02:35:47.450 --> 02:35:51.470
But in fact it is excavations
that have been carried out first

02:35:51.470 --> 02:35:55.610
by University of Hamburg and then
more recently by the Universities

02:35:55.610 --> 02:35:57.780
of Amsterdam and Ghent in Belgium.

02:35:57.780 --> 02:36:00.640
At the site of the
so-called [foreign name]

02:36:00.640 --> 02:36:07.440
that have actually come up with
all different kinds of evidence.

02:36:07.440 --> 02:36:10.210
Particularly from the
[foreign name] site

02:36:10.210 --> 02:36:15.400
that recent radio carbon dates have
actually been pushing back to sort

02:36:15.400 --> 02:36:18.310
of the first presence of
settlement at that site

02:36:18.310 --> 02:36:19.610
to the end of the 9th century.

02:36:19.610 --> 02:36:22.550
So that sort of brings us within
touching distance as it were

02:36:22.550 --> 02:36:25.400
of that sort of traditional
foundation date.

02:36:25.400 --> 02:36:28.110
So that's sort of one
important achievement

02:36:28.110 --> 02:36:30.190
that I would like to highlight.

02:36:30.190 --> 02:36:32.050
But what you see in
the larger photo,

02:36:32.050 --> 02:36:35.900
which is sort of not
particularly enticing or sort

02:36:35.900 --> 02:36:37.650
of attractive you might think.

02:36:37.650 --> 02:36:39.810
But in many ways it
is, because in one

02:36:39.810 --> 02:36:43.260
of those industrial
or artisanal areas.

02:36:43.260 --> 02:36:48.380
And in this case a fairly
early ironworking site

02:36:48.380 --> 02:36:51.460
at ancient Carthage.

02:36:54.450 --> 02:36:57.710
Another important settlement
site where Phoenicians settled

02:36:57.710 --> 02:37:01.200
down very early is on the
southeast, of the southwest,

02:37:01.200 --> 02:37:03.150
sorry, of the isle of Sardinia.

02:37:03.150 --> 02:37:06.200
In fact on a little island just
off the island of Sardinia itself.

02:37:06.200 --> 02:37:08.750
The little Island of Santiago
where the ancient site

02:37:08.750 --> 02:37:13.310
of Sulkey was established right
in the middle of the modern town,

02:37:13.310 --> 02:37:16.130
as you can see on this aerial.

02:37:16.130 --> 02:37:19.670
There you can see most of
the remains are Roman period

02:37:19.670 --> 02:37:21.850
or Punic later and so on.

02:37:21.850 --> 02:37:24.870
But it's within that
highlighted area there.

02:37:24.870 --> 02:37:26.170
That's why there's one area

02:37:26.170 --> 02:37:29.370
where much older foundations
of a house were found.

02:37:29.370 --> 02:37:34.070
And particularly, zooming much
more in detail at those remains,

02:37:34.070 --> 02:37:36.370
we've actually got foundations

02:37:36.370 --> 02:37:40.730
of a house probably possibly two
houses here that were established

02:37:40.730 --> 02:37:42.960
in the early or mid-8th century.

02:37:42.960 --> 02:37:45.270
So that's a little bit later
than the sort of evidence

02:37:45.270 --> 02:37:46.890
that we've been getting
from Carthage.

02:37:46.890 --> 02:37:50.120
But here what was very
important to establish as well,

02:37:50.120 --> 02:37:52.420
these were new foundations.

02:37:52.420 --> 02:37:53.720
There was nothing before that.

02:37:53.720 --> 02:37:56.030
These were established
on an empty site.

02:37:56.030 --> 02:38:00.380
And the life from the
materials as we can find,

02:38:00.380 --> 02:38:01.700
that people were living here.

02:38:01.700 --> 02:38:04.690 position:56%
The kind of houses that they were
building there, they seem to be sort

02:38:04.690 --> 02:38:07.600
of fully fledged Phoenician houses.

02:38:07.600 --> 02:38:09.900
And some of the pottery
sort of illustrated

02:38:09.900 --> 02:38:12.960
in that drawing there actually
find some very close matches

02:38:12.960 --> 02:38:15.860
to material known from Tyre.

02:38:15.860 --> 02:38:21.080
But what also should be noted here,
Sardinia wasn't empty of course.

02:38:21.080 --> 02:38:24.110
The island was already
inhabited by local Sardinians,

02:38:24.110 --> 02:38:26.350 position:56%
people of so-called Nuragic culture.

02:38:26.350 --> 02:38:29.200
And some of their material culture,
some potsherds have been found

02:38:29.200 --> 02:38:34.350
within this early Phoenician
context as well.

02:38:34.350 --> 02:38:37.300
Moving further west, really
sort of into the far west

02:38:37.300 --> 02:38:39.910
of the Mediterranean,
if not just beyond,

02:38:39.910 --> 02:38:44.270
as we're just outside
the Strait of Gibraltar

02:38:44.270 --> 02:38:48.330
in Cadis on the modern Lucia.

02:38:48.330 --> 02:38:51.520
And here we are overlooking
the area, the salt marshes.

02:38:51.520 --> 02:38:56.610
The vast wetlands that sort of
make up that part of the coast.

02:38:56.610 --> 02:38:59.300
This has been long an
archaeological problem here.

02:38:59.300 --> 02:39:01.560
Because stray finds
we're turning up,

02:39:01.560 --> 02:39:04.470
like this little Phoenician
statuette that was actually dragged

02:39:04.470 --> 02:39:07.380
up from the sea, so without
any precise foundation.

02:39:07.380 --> 02:39:11.030
So if you look it up in
literature of on web sources,

02:39:11.030 --> 02:39:15.970 position:56%
you will find widely varying dates
for this little statuette because by

02:39:15.970 --> 02:39:18.470
and large it cannot be
dated with any precision.

02:39:18.470 --> 02:39:21.190
Various kinds of Phoenician
amphorae clearly recognizable

02:39:21.190 --> 02:39:22.990
as such were turning
up from various places.

02:39:22.990 --> 02:39:25.980
But not with any sort
of clear contexts.

02:39:25.980 --> 02:39:30.620
But all of this has now sort of
been changed in a very dramatic way

02:39:30.620 --> 02:39:34.120
because of what really has
been commercial excavations,

02:39:34.120 --> 02:39:38.210
salvage interventions going
on to do with building

02:39:38.210 --> 02:39:42.920
within the historical town of Cadis
over the last ten years or so.

02:39:42.920 --> 02:39:47.400
And evidence that has sort of
only just been published really.

02:39:47.400 --> 02:39:50.210
Now what's been found there at
the site called [foreign name]

02:39:50.210 --> 02:39:55.560
because it's actually under
this historical theater

02:39:55.560 --> 02:40:00.440
in downtown Cadis, that a whole
Phoenician neighborhood basically

02:40:00.440 --> 02:40:01.950
has been brought to light.

02:40:01.950 --> 02:40:05.760
There's eight houses contained
in three separate buildings

02:40:05.760 --> 02:40:08.660
with a street and a small
side alley connecting to it,

02:40:08.660 --> 02:40:11.220
sort of connecting them up.

02:40:11.220 --> 02:40:14.780
From the nature of the evidence,
it's actually very clear

02:40:14.780 --> 02:40:17.900
that several of the buildings
at least had several stories

02:40:17.900 --> 02:40:20.660
as you can see in this
reconstruction here.

02:40:20.660 --> 02:40:23.250
And the site has actually
recently been made accessible

02:40:23.250 --> 02:40:25.240
to the public under the theater.

02:40:25.240 --> 02:40:28.200
So if any of you would
happen to go to St. Lucia,

02:40:28.200 --> 02:40:32.160
Cadis should definitely
be a place to go there.

02:40:32.160 --> 02:40:35.600
The excellent state of
preservation and excavation

02:40:35.600 --> 02:40:38.140
of this evidence has clearly,

02:40:38.140 --> 02:40:42.720 position:56%
very clearly demonstrated the people
here were living Phoenician style.

02:40:42.720 --> 02:40:48.150
There's no less than five
or six bread ovens really

02:40:48.150 --> 02:40:51.980
to make this flatbread that have
been found in those places there.

02:40:51.980 --> 02:40:55.830
Again, all of this dating to
the very end of the 9th century,

02:40:55.830 --> 02:40:57.130
sort of early 8th century.

02:40:57.130 --> 02:41:01.160
So we're back at the very early
dates, coinciding roughly in time

02:41:01.160 --> 02:41:02.860
with the foundation of Carthage.

02:41:02.860 --> 02:41:07.240
And what's remarkable therefore,
at that very early date,

02:41:07.240 --> 02:41:11.330 position:56%
people were already going as far as
the very edges of the Mediterranean,

02:41:11.330 --> 02:41:18.240
venturing out at least into
the opening up of the Atlantic.

02:41:18.240 --> 02:41:21.340
So what we have here clearly
therefore is a Phoenician migrant

02:41:21.340 --> 02:41:26.430
community setting themselves up
not just for making a few bucks

02:41:26.430 --> 02:41:30.240
on the shoreline or exchanging
something on the beaches or so.

02:41:30.240 --> 02:41:31.680 position:56%
This is something totally different.

02:41:31.680 --> 02:41:33.350
This is a very substantial,

02:41:33.350 --> 02:41:38.610
well-established trading
and migrant settlement.

02:41:38.610 --> 02:41:40.790
What's interesting though, and
that's a little fragment you see

02:41:40.790 --> 02:41:42.280
in the very middle
of my slide there,

02:41:42.280 --> 02:41:45.800 position:56%
is it's not just Phoenician material
culture that's being found here.

02:41:45.800 --> 02:41:50.870
This pot that you see there is a
vessel from the island of Sardinia

02:41:50.870 --> 02:41:52.640
and interestingly not
a Phoenician one.

02:41:52.640 --> 02:41:57.930
But this is one, a so-called
Nuragic jug that belongs

02:41:57.930 --> 02:42:00.380 position:56%
within the Nuragic/Sardinia culture.

02:42:00.380 --> 02:42:03.640
So the island of Sardinia,
sort of situated centrally

02:42:03.640 --> 02:42:06.790
in the west Mediterranean, is
one of those important places.

02:42:06.790 --> 02:42:09.920 position:56%
A very large island, one of the
largest islands of the Mediterranean

02:42:09.920 --> 02:42:11.920
that really played a key role

02:42:11.920 --> 02:42:14.590
in Phoenician expansion
and its contacts.

02:42:14.590 --> 02:42:18.120
The creating of those
contacts across and spanning

02:42:18.120 --> 02:42:20.530
over the entire Mediterranean.

02:42:20.530 --> 02:42:24.790
And you're looking here at
this wonderful bay which is one

02:42:24.790 --> 02:42:28.830
of the best anchorages in this
part of the Mediterranean.

02:42:28.830 --> 02:42:35.800 position:56%
This site and the next one that I'll
be talking about, these two dots

02:42:35.800 --> 02:42:37.640
that you see here, the
sites of St. Bernia

02:42:37.640 --> 02:42:41.220
and Suraki actually have
come up with evidence.

02:42:41.220 --> 02:42:44.580
And again in the last
5-10 years with evidence

02:42:44.580 --> 02:42:47.300
of a different mode of being.

02:42:47.300 --> 02:42:50.220
A different mode of
migrating and a different mode

02:42:50.220 --> 02:42:54.710 position:56%
of commercial interaction within the
Phoenician world that we have seen.

02:42:54.710 --> 02:42:56.310
Because these two sites, St. Bernia

02:42:56.310 --> 02:42:58.490
and Suraki are not
Phoenician settlements.

02:42:58.490 --> 02:43:01.940
These are indigenous Nuragic
Sardinian settlements.

02:43:01.940 --> 02:43:06.260
But we've got clear evidence
here of Phoenician activities

02:43:06.260 --> 02:43:10.120
and in fact sort of fairly
permanent presence in those sites.

02:43:10.120 --> 02:43:14.240
And in fact, the amphora that you
see here is a local production.

02:43:14.240 --> 02:43:15.700
It's not a Canaanite jar.

02:43:15.700 --> 02:43:17.160
It's not a Phoenician amphora.

02:43:17.160 --> 02:43:18.460
It's locally produced.

02:43:18.460 --> 02:43:21.150
The type is sort of
specific to Sardinia.

02:43:21.150 --> 02:43:26.110
But it is clearly sort of based
on the Phoenician prototypes.

02:43:26.110 --> 02:43:29.900
And this type of jar is called
St. Bernia jar because that's

02:43:29.900 --> 02:43:32.860
where it was first recognized,
has actually been found

02:43:32.860 --> 02:43:34.920
in Carthage itself as well.

02:43:34.920 --> 02:43:37.800
And probably now in Spain too.

02:43:37.800 --> 02:43:40.500
And all of this goes together
with all of those other elements

02:43:40.500 --> 02:43:42.570
that make up these
material connections.

02:43:42.570 --> 02:43:43.870
There's some Greek pottery,

02:43:43.870 --> 02:43:46.070
some very early Greek pottery
as you can see as well.

02:43:46.070 --> 02:43:47.990
We're talking near the
end of the 9th century.

02:43:47.990 --> 02:43:52.690
So again we're back to the very
early horizon Phoenician expansion

02:43:52.690 --> 02:43:54.000
in the west.

02:43:54.000 --> 02:43:59.140
And of course those sort of
shapeless blocks that are lying

02:43:59.140 --> 02:44:00.490
at the foot of the amphora.

02:44:00.490 --> 02:44:03.320
These are broken up bronze ingots.

02:44:03.320 --> 02:44:08.010
So again, sort of trade in metal
very well demonstrated here.

02:44:08.010 --> 02:44:12.730
This slide gives you an indication
of that site of St. Bernia

02:44:12.730 --> 02:44:15.430
which you clearly see this
is totally alien in a way

02:44:15.430 --> 02:44:17.480
to Phoenician architecture.

02:44:17.480 --> 02:44:19.090
Because in fact it isn't.

02:44:19.090 --> 02:44:22.280
It is what the site of
St. Bernia looks like.

02:44:22.280 --> 02:44:25.180
Typical late bronze age,
iron age architecture

02:44:25.180 --> 02:44:28.210
with all the specificities
that I won't be going into.

02:44:28.210 --> 02:44:29.510
But what we're looking

02:44:29.510 --> 02:44:33.850
at is therefore present
Phoenician context that's

02:44:33.850 --> 02:44:39.110 position:56%
in this case difficult to say within
a well-established local complex.

02:44:39.110 --> 02:44:42.280
For better understanding of
how that sort of embedding

02:44:42.280 --> 02:44:48.380
of the Phoenician complex could
work in a Nuragic Sardinia context,

02:44:48.380 --> 02:44:49.740
we need to look at this other side.

02:44:49.740 --> 02:44:54.410
Suraki, sort of lower down
the west coast of Sardinia,

02:44:54.410 --> 02:44:57.160 position:56%
which is in fact the site where I
am directing the excavation project.

02:44:57.160 --> 02:45:01.340
At the moment we have got
very extensive evidence

02:45:01.340 --> 02:45:04.440
of Phoenician material, like
this mushroom lipped jar

02:45:04.440 --> 02:45:06.860 position:56%
which actually comes from this site.

02:45:06.860 --> 02:45:08.790
And some other Greek
and local material.

02:45:08.790 --> 02:45:10.240
But it is mostly through --

02:45:10.240 --> 02:45:12.570
and again sort of connecting
to the previous paper,

02:45:12.570 --> 02:45:17.390
through archaeometric,
technical, scientific investigation

02:45:17.390 --> 02:45:18.690
where the pottery was made.

02:45:18.690 --> 02:45:22.410
But also through X-ray analysis
understanding how handles are

02:45:22.410 --> 02:45:26.770
shaped, how the pot itself was
shaped, how rims were connected.

02:45:26.770 --> 02:45:30.570
That gives us an insight into the
very small details of the skills

02:45:30.570 --> 02:45:32.850
of artisans, of the
ceramic artisans.

02:45:32.850 --> 02:45:38.940
This shows us actually that even if
pots look they are Sardinian style

02:45:38.940 --> 02:45:44.060 position:56%
or they are Phoenician style, we can
see that we must have had masters

02:45:44.060 --> 02:45:46.830
and trainees of different
cultural backgrounds.

02:45:46.830 --> 02:45:48.440
Because we can see a mixing up,

02:45:48.440 --> 02:45:51.680
the body of the pot made
in a Phoenician style.

02:45:51.680 --> 02:45:55.400 position:56%
The pot made to look like a
Phoenician cooking pot for instance.

02:45:55.400 --> 02:46:00.430
But the handle or the rim made
with Nuragic indigenous techniques.

02:46:00.430 --> 02:46:03.890
So it's really the kind of
interactions that you can only get

02:46:03.890 --> 02:46:06.370
when people are sort of
living and working together

02:46:06.370 --> 02:46:09.740 position:56%
on the same place for quite a while.

02:46:09.740 --> 02:46:13.250
And it would land here,
this brief survey,

02:46:13.250 --> 02:46:16.600
with another material dimension
of what those connections are.

02:46:16.600 --> 02:46:18.150
It's actually the ships themselves.

02:46:18.150 --> 02:46:20.810
We've heard about the
Uluburun wreck.

02:46:20.810 --> 02:46:23.890
We've heard a reference to
the [inaudible] wreck earlier.

02:46:23.890 --> 02:46:26.260
This is another sort of
one that's just beginning

02:46:26.260 --> 02:46:29.660
to make the literature
because it's so recent.

02:46:29.660 --> 02:46:33.610
This is one of two ships that
were found just off the beach

02:46:33.610 --> 02:46:37.020
of [inaudible] south of
[inaudible] in [Spanish name]

02:46:37.020 --> 02:46:40.720
on the Spanish Mediterranean coast.

02:46:40.720 --> 02:46:45.300
This has been excavated and that
actually dates to the 7th century

02:46:45.300 --> 02:46:48.460
and it gives us some
material evidence as well.

